idance of inbreeding seems incontrovertible, but just how injurious inbreeding really is for successive generations remains an open question. Nor has there been any conclusion to the debate over Freud’s view that the incest taboo is necessary because humans are sexually attracted to their closest relatives—a claim countered by Westermarck's argument for the sexually inhibiting effects of early childhood association. This book brings together contributions from the fields of genetics, behavioral biology, primatology, biological and social anthropology, philosophy, and psychiatry which reexamine these questions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aConsanguinity. 0aConsanguinité. 0aInbreeding. 0aIncest. 0aInceste. 0aTaboo. 0aTabou. 4aAnthropology -- Cultural and Social Anthropology. 4aAnthropology -- Science, Technology, and Medical Anthropology. 4aPhilosophy -- Social Theory. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Human Sexuality (see also SOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Sexuality).2bisacsh1 aArnhart, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBateson, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBittles, Alan H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurham, William H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurham, William H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErickson, Mark T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGates, Hill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPusey, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScheidel, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSesardic, Neven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolf, Arthur 